I have are large number of REST endpoints, written in Java &amp; Spring. The endpoints mostly look like this simplified example.

- `GET /cars?` =&gt; Get all cards
- `GET /cars/&lt;id&gt;` =&gt; Get single car
- `PATCH /car/&lt;id&gt;` =&gt; update car
- `PATCH /cars-bulk` =&gt; update car (bulk)
- `POST /cars` =&gt; create car
- `POST /cars-bulk` =&gt; create cars (bulk)

Let&#39;s say I have this class:


    public class CarDTO {
      private String id;
      private String make;
      private String model;
      private String owner;
      private boolean isAvailable;
    }

And let&#39;s say I have this service signature:

    public interface CarService {
      CarDTO getCarById(String id);
      List&lt;CarDTO&gt; getCars(CarDTO filter);
      CarDTO updateCar(CarDTO car);
      CarDTO createCar(CarDTO car);
      List&lt;BulkUpdateResult&gt; updateCars(List&lt;CarDTO&gt; car);
      List&lt;BulkUpdateResult&gt; createCars(List&lt;CarDTO&gt; car);
    }

In this case, DTOs are shared across different service methods. This comes with the problem that the consumers of these interfaces don&#39;t know which fields they need to set in the DTO for each method call.

For example:
 - `getCarById` and `getCars` calls returns all fields, except `isAvailable`
 - `updateCar` / `updateCars` is only allowed to update the `owner` field
 - `createCar` / `createCars` can set any field, except the `id` (generated by service)

This can be implemented using validators and manual description of the APIs, but I prefer to have self-explanatory call signatures for certain endpoints. If a field is not supposed to be produced or consumed, I don&#39;t want to make it part of the call signature.

One solution I have tried is to create DTOs (`CarGetDTO`, `CarUpdateDTO`, `CarCreateDTO`) for every endpoint like so: 

    public interface CarService {
      CarGetDTO getCarById(String id);
      List&lt;CarGetDTO&gt; getCars(CarGetDTO filter);
      CarGetDTO updateCar(CarUpdateDTO car);
      CarGetDTO createCar(CarUpdateDTO car);
      List&lt;BulkUpdateResult&gt; updateCars(List&lt;CarCreateDTO&gt; car);
      List&lt;BulkUpdateResult&gt; createCars(List&lt;CarCreateDTO&gt; car);
    }

This however becomes incredibly complex with a large code base, code duplication and complex business requirements.

One way to solve this, that I can think of, is leverage polymorphism, but it makes the code mode complex and harder to understand.

    public abstract class CarDTO {
      private String owner;
    }

    public class CarCreateDTO extends CarDTO  {
      private String make;
      private String model;
    }

    public class CarGetDTO extends CarCreateDTO  {
      private String id; // duplicate code
    }

    public class CarUpdateDTO extends CarCreateDTO  {
      private String id; // duplicate code
      private boolean isAvailable;
    }



